NIB never fired Grendel P12 .380 Semi-Auto Pistol 
Grendel was a hot manufacturer of mostly high capacity weapons in the early 90's. 
When the first assault weapon ban came, Grendel silently faded away. They were resurrected 4-5 years later as KelTec, same owner, at same Florida location. Today, KelTec is the third largest manufacturer of handguns in the USA. If this Grendel resembles a KelTec you've seen that is why. The slide, frame and firing mechanisms are made of high strength steel, with high-impact strength polymer material for the grip, mag well, trigger, trigger guard and magazines. 

This is a lot of firepower in a very small package. The .380 cartridge is no slouch and many feel that it's about top of the line for a truly concealable pistol. This P12 is much smaller and lighter than compact high capacity 9mm's and .40's handguns. Gun comes all original; in the factory plastic case, manual, parts list and 2 magazines. Manual is 14 pages, very thorough on; features, operation, disassembly, parts and cleaning. 

Magazines holds 11 rounds, with one in the chamber (P12 = 11+1).

A stainless steel barrel requires less maintenance and is corrosion resistant. The pistol adapts to different hand sizes easily with interchangeable back straps (included). A reversible magazine release button can be mounted on either side and can quickly be replaced by a smaller and larger size button (optional). title: For Sale:              MARLIN  PAPOOSE SURVIVAL RIFLE
postcontent:
The Marlin Model 70P, also known as the Marlin Papoose, is a .22 Long Rifle semi-automatic rifle manufactured by Marlin Firearms. The rifle is notable for its portability; it is less than 21 inches (530 mm) in length when disassembled and weighs 3.25 pounds. Disassembly requires loosening a barrel retention nut by hand or with a supplied tool. It is designed as a hiker and camper utility rifle, and appeals to the same market as the AR-7. The Model 70P is based on the earlier Marlin Model 70 (currently listed as Model 795) that has a fixed barrel and conventional stock. Its semi-automatic action originated with the Marlin Model 60. The Marlin Model 70PSS variant has a synthetic stock and stainless steel barrel.

The rifle has an open rear sight and ramp front sight with high visibility orange post surrounded by a cutaway hood. The receiver has an integral .22 tip-off scope mounting rail. Swivel studs for a carrying strap are embedded in the synthetic stock. Included Marlin accessories are a 7 round metal magazine, a tool for adjusting the barrel nut, and a padded nylon carrying case designed to float in water. Optional accessories from Marlin include 7 and 10 round metal magazines   10/22

title: For Sale/Trade:  Would like to trade This S&W .38 Special Revolver for a Snub-Nose Revolver for Concealed Carry
postcontent: For Sale/Trade is this very nice and fully functional Smith and Wesson Revolver, know as the Military & Police.  It is chambered in .38 Special and has a 4in Barrel.  The Military & Police model was built first in 1905 and this one is the 1905 - 3rd Change, manufactured in 1910 (Verified with the S&W Historical Department).  The pistol is in very good condition with the only real wear being from its life in a holster.  The blue is about 85% to 90% condition.  There is almost no rust on the frame and the barrel bore is very bright and free of any pits.  The pistol appears that is has always been cleaned and serviced.  The hammer and trigger are as smooth as butter on glass and the cylinder locks up tightly.  The trigger in the single action position is 1.5 to 2lbs and only about 5 to 6 pounds in the double action function.  This is a classic S&W that is used just enough that you can shoot it without hurting its value.  These old frames were not built to handle hot loads so Plus-P loads are a no-no in this pistol.  She's quite a pleasure to shoot and you can feel the quality.  High book on this pistol is $1450.  It is fairly priced at $650 (well below it's 85% Book value).  The pistol comes with a vintage and well worn holster.  What I would like to trade this revolver for:  A Smith & Wesson or Colt Snub-Nose Revolver.  I will look at others if they are of quality construction.  Send me an email with your contact information and any trade offers and I'll get back with youASAP.
